'''Linea nigra''' ([[Latin]] for "black line") is a dark vertical line that appears on the abdomen during about three quarters of all [[pregnancy|pregnancies]].<ref name="pmid7832550">{{cite journal |author=Estève E, Saudeau L, Pierre F, Barruet K, Vaillant L, Lorette G |title=[Physiological cutaneous signs in normal pregnancy: a study of 60 pregnant women] |language=French |journal=Ann Dermatol Venereol |volume=121 |issue=3 |pages= 227–231 |year=1994 |pmid=7832550 |doi= |url=}}</ref> The brownish streak is usually about a centimeter in width. The line runs vertically along the midline of the [[abdomen]] from the [[pubis (bone)|pubis]] to the [[Navel|umbilicus]], but can also run from the pubis to the top of the abdomen.<ref>[http://pregnancyandbaby.com/pregnancy/baby/Whats-my-line-All-about-the-linea-nigra-4210.htm She Knows Network: "What's that line? All about linea nigra"]</ref> Linea nigra is due to increased [[melanocyte-stimulating hormone]] made by the placenta,<ref name="Reproductive System at a Glance">{{cite book|last=Heffner|first=Linda|title=The Reproductive System at a Glance|year=2010|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-1-4051-9452-5|pages=51}}</ref> which also causes [[melasma]] and darkened [[nipples]].
Fair-skinned women show this phenomenon less often than women with darker pigmentation.{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}} Before it appears, it may be more faintly visible as a white line.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}

